1
00:00:30,344 --> 00:00:32,045
<i> [News Theme Music Playing]</i>

2
00:00:41,241 --> 00:00:43,766
<i>You have a very great opportunity...</i>

3
00:00:44,377 --> 00:00:47,210
<i>... not merely to provide bread and butter...</i>

4
00:00:47,681 --> 00:00:50,514
<i>... not merely to keep people from starving.</i>

5
00:00:50,617 --> 00:00:53,882
<i>You have the further
great social opportunity...</i>

6
00:00:54,988 --> 00:00:57,218
<i>... of inculcating the understanding...</i>

7
00:00:57,290 --> 00:01:00,225
<i>... that we've got to build
from the bottom up...</i>

8
00:01:00,327 --> 00:01:02,400
<i>... and not merely supply food
from the top down.</i>

9
00:01:02,410 --> 00:01:06,280
<i> [Theme Music Playing]</i>

10
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:10,128
<i>[Announcer]: The First Lady,
about to take an aerial holiday...</i>

11
00:01:10,203 --> 00:01:12,467
<i>... has a word to say before she goes.</i>

12
00:01:12,639 --> 00:01:16,075
<i>I'm very glad to be here...</i>

13
00:01:16,176 --> 00:01:20,977
<i>... and I'm just starting on
an unofficial trip to Puerto Rico...</i>

14
00:01:21,481 --> 00:01:26,043
<i>... hoping to see something
of a very beautiful island and its people.</i>

15
00:01:26,419 --> 00:01:30,014
<i>[Announcer]:  Mrs. Roosevelt gets ready
for the first over-ocean flight...</i>

16
00:01:30,156 --> 00:01:32,647
<i>... ever made by a president's wife.</i>

17
00:01:32,892 --> 00:01:36,293
<i>Off to Haiti,
landing safely a few hours later...</i>

18
00:01:36,429 --> 00:01:38,761
<i>... then Puerto Rico and the Virgin Islands.</i>

19
00:01:38,832 --> 00:01:43,531
<i>A triple hop of 1,250 miles
for the flying First Lady.</i>

20
00:01:47,674 --> 00:01:51,303
<i>Emotion continued high
in this small country courthouse...</i>

21
00:01:51,411 --> 00:01:53,845
<i>... as young Leonard Hill
and Wesley Bruckner...</i>

22
00:01:53,913 --> 00:01:57,576
<i>... after six weeks of one
of the century's grisliest murder trials...</i>

23
00:01:57,650 --> 00:01:59,777
<i>... were sentenced to life imprisonment.</i>

24
00:02:00,120 --> 00:02:02,054
<i>During the course of the trial...</i>

25
00:02:02,122 --> 00:02:05,057
<i>... the jury was shown photographs
such as these...</i>

26
00:02:05,125 --> 00:02:08,925
<i>... depicting the brutal mutilation killing
of Ellie Banner...</i>

27
00:02:08,995 --> 00:02:10,678
<i>... one of Braddock's
most respected citizens.</i>

28
00:02:10,745 --> 00:02:12,001
<i>[Crowd Shouting]</i>

29
00:02:12,198 --> 00:02:15,725
<i>There was a tense moment as crowds,
displeased at the verdict...</i>

30
00:02:15,869 --> 00:02:20,238
<i>... threatened the orderly departure
of the young killers from the courthouse.</i>

31
00:02:21,241 --> 00:02:24,233
<i>Leaving moments later
are the convicted men's mothers...</i>

32
00:02:24,310 --> 00:02:26,437
<i>... Adelle Bruckner and Helen Hill.</i>

33
00:02:26,713 --> 00:02:29,307
<i>During the sensation-packed days
of the trial...</i>

34
00:02:29,416 --> 00:02:31,407
<i>... Mrs. Bruckner and Mrs. Hill...</i>

35
00:02:31,484 --> 00:02:35,921
<i>... have been subjected to nearly
as much public curiosity as their sons.</i>

36
00:02:37,424 --> 00:02:41,451
<i>And so the ordeal comes to an end
for these two women...</i>

37
00:02:41,594 --> 00:02:45,360
<i>... as their sons go to prison for life.</i>

38
00:05:04,871 --> 00:05:06,896
Billy, get us out of here.

39
00:05:07,155 --> 00:05:08,288
[Car Horn Honking]

40
00:05:08,808 --> 00:05:10,901
Do you have a handkerchief?

41
00:05:11,344 --> 00:05:12,276
Sure.

42
00:05:11,643 --> 00:05:12,700
[Horn Honking]

43
00:05:12,710 --> 00:05:13,977
[Adelle Sighs]

44
00:05:14,781 --> 00:05:17,875
You're not
going to cry, are you?
You never cry.

45
00:05:17,315 --> 00:05:18,649
[Crowd Thumping On Car]

46
00:05:18,716 --> 00:05:20,517
Oh, no.

47
00:05:21,321 --> 00:05:22,379
What happened?

48
00:05:22,655 --> 00:05:25,618
Somebody cut me.
Somebody out there cut me.

49
00:05:25,623 --> 00:05:27,123
[Horn Honking]

50
00:05:28,061 --> 00:05:29,551
[Helen]:
The handkerchief,
put the handkerchief on it.

51
00:05:30,964 --> 00:05:32,226
Billy, hurry!

52
00:05:46,811 --> 00:05:48,078
[Car Door Closing]

53
00:05:57,824 --> 00:06:00,019
[Adelle]: I know it's
against your religion, Helen...

54
00:06:00,093 --> 00:06:02,186
...but you better have a shot of gin.

55
00:06:02,262 --> 00:06:04,890
Adelle, I'd rather have a first aid kit.

56
00:06:04,998 --> 00:06:07,432
Yeah, of course.

57
00:06:18,077 --> 00:06:20,375
I call that real class.

58
00:06:20,446 --> 00:06:22,073
What?

59
00:06:22,382 --> 00:06:25,818
The way you didn't scream or anything.

60
00:06:26,719 --> 00:06:28,619
I'd have raised the roof.

61
00:06:30,890 --> 00:06:32,755
Iodine first, dear.

62
00:06:37,230 --> 00:06:39,221
Go ahead. Go on.

63
00:06:46,105 --> 00:06:48,403
And you never saw who did it?

64
00:06:49,242 --> 00:06:51,506
I didn't even feel it.

65
00:06:51,678 --> 00:06:54,511
I just looked down,
and my palm was full of blood.

66
00:06:54,881 --> 00:06:57,941
What kind of a screwball
would do such a thing?

67
00:07:00,753 --> 00:07:01,742
There.

68
00:07:01,821 --> 00:07:03,345
Thank you, Adelle.

69
00:07:03,690 --> 00:07:06,090
How about a little shot of gin now?

70
00:07:09,077 --> 00:07:10,601
[Exhales]

71
00:07:10,863 --> 00:07:12,262
Holy Moses...

72
00:07:13,266 --> 00:07:17,066
...I still have a heap to get done
if I'm going to get out of here on Friday.

73
00:07:17,403 --> 00:07:19,769
I think I'm going to have that shot of gin.

74
00:07:33,586 --> 00:07:36,578
I didn't tell you.
But you know what I've decided?

75
00:07:36,656 --> 00:07:38,817
I decided that the school in California...

76
00:07:38,891 --> 00:07:42,190
...is going to be all different, just for kids.

77
00:07:42,261 --> 00:07:45,025
Out there in Hollywood,
kids are the cat's meow.

78
00:07:45,465 --> 00:07:46,625
Cat's meow?

79
00:07:46,699 --> 00:07:48,997
Since Shirley Temple, you know?

80
00:07:49,469 --> 00:07:51,334
You have heard of Shirley Temple.

81
00:07:51,571 --> 00:07:55,371
I hardly ever go to the movies,
but I've heard of Shirley Temple.

82
00:07:55,541 --> 00:07:58,101
You know, out there in Hollywood...

83
00:07:58,344 --> 00:08:01,973
...all the parents are crazy
to get their kids in the movies.

84
00:08:02,548 --> 00:08:05,847
And somebody has to teach them how
to sing and dance, so...

85
00:08:07,053 --> 00:08:08,918
...why shouldn't I help?

86
00:08:09,956 --> 00:08:13,050
Won't you mind being
so far away from your boy?

87
00:08:13,126 --> 00:08:16,562
Of course I will.
But what can I do about it?

88
00:08:17,764 --> 00:08:21,200
He turned on me. He really turned on me.

89
00:08:21,300 --> 00:08:24,167
You saw. I just don't understand it.

90
00:08:24,804 --> 00:08:26,635
I did everything I could for him.

91
00:08:27,206 --> 00:08:29,640
It wasn't my fault
that his father took a powder.

92
00:08:35,081 --> 00:08:37,611
Men can be quite a bit lower
than the angels.

93
00:08:37,614 --> 00:08:39,049
[Telephone Ringing]

94
00:08:41,154 --> 00:08:42,746
That's for sure.

95
00:08:45,324 --> 00:08:47,519
Adelle's New York School of Dance.

96
00:08:48,194 --> 00:08:49,320
Hello?

97
00:08:50,029 --> 00:08:51,758
[Adelle]: This is she.

98
00:08:52,198 --> 00:08:53,529
Yeah, hold on.
It's, umm,

99
00:08:54,066 --> 00:08:56,534
someone with asthma for you.

100
00:09:01,707 --> 00:09:03,197
Hello?

101
00:09:05,845 --> 00:09:10,214
<i>[Man]: I thought you'd
like to know, I'm the one
who cut you today.</i>

102
00:09:10,650 --> 00:09:13,915
<i>- Why?
- I wanted to see you bleed.</i>

103
00:09:14,220 --> 00:09:16,313
<i>Like Ellie Banner.</i>

104
00:09:16,622 --> 00:09:19,113
<i>I wanted to be sure you can.</i>

105
00:09:19,425 --> 00:09:23,020
<i>You'll bleed, all right.
So will the other one.</i>

106
00:09:23,196 --> 00:09:26,461
You have no right to talk to me like that.

107
00:09:27,066 --> 00:09:28,658
[Adelle]: What's going on?

108
00:09:29,735 --> 00:09:32,329
<i>Those boys should have gone
to the gallows.</i>

109
00:09:32,405 --> 00:09:35,135
<i>Somebody's got to pay
for what they did to Ellie.</i>

110
00:09:35,208 --> 00:09:37,870
<i>And somebody's going to.</i>

111
00:09:38,244 --> 00:09:39,541
<i>You...</i>

112
00:09:40,046 --> 00:09:41,479
<i>... and her.</i>

113
00:09:42,215 --> 00:09:44,775
<i>Wherever you are I'm going to...</i>

114
00:09:44,917 --> 00:09:46,509
I'll call the police.

115
00:09:47,585 --> 00:09:48,985
[Telephone Dialing]

116
00:09:49,789 --> 00:09:50,778
Don't.

117
00:09:51,624 --> 00:09:54,616
No. We'll be all over the papers again.

118
00:09:54,994 --> 00:09:57,019
I can't take that anymore.

119
00:09:57,096 --> 00:09:58,961
Th...that man's dangerous.

120
00:09:59,131 --> 00:10:02,658
Helen, how do you know?
He may be just a harmless crank.

121
00:10:06,005 --> 00:10:08,496
Please, don't do anything yet.

122
00:10:08,774 --> 00:10:11,504
Honestly, Helen, I can't stand any more.

123
00:10:20,653 --> 00:10:22,177
I don't understand.

124
00:10:22,889 --> 00:10:25,414
Wes, saying that he hated me...

125
00:10:26,092 --> 00:10:29,220
...and that I was too busy
when he needed me.

126
00:10:28,909 --> 00:10:30,343
[Chuckles]

127
00:10:31,097 --> 00:10:34,624
I was busy dancing my feet off
to earn a buck so we could eat.

128
00:10:36,235 --> 00:10:38,226
I did everything I could.

129
00:10:40,840 --> 00:10:44,105
No matter how bad things get...

130
00:10:44,343 --> 00:10:46,811
...you must always tell yourself...

131
00:10:46,879 --> 00:10:49,871
...there's a reason,
there has to be a reason.

132
00:10:52,385 --> 00:10:54,444
- Up there?
- Yes.

133
00:10:55,119 --> 00:10:56,326
[Sobs]

134
00:10:58,057 --> 00:11:00,491
I...I need a reason
down here.

135
00:11:00,826 --> 00:11:01,850
I do.

136
00:11:07,500 --> 00:11:10,697
Helen, Why don't...
why don't you come with me
to California?

137
00:11:12,471 --> 00:11:13,597
Well, I--I...

138
00:11:13,673 --> 00:11:16,733
D-d-don't worry.
I have a little
money socked away.

139
00:11:17,109 --> 00:11:20,840
Enough for two train tickets,
if you don't mind riding coach.

140
00:11:21,013 --> 00:11:24,972
And--and I'll still
have enough to get the school
going somehow.

141
00:11:25,484 --> 00:11:27,475
I'm so glad you asked me.

142
00:11:27,920 --> 00:11:30,912
I didn't want to be the one
that suggested it.

143
00:11:34,961 --> 00:11:37,191
You're quite a girl.

144
00:11:39,131 --> 00:11:41,429
You really are, Mrs. Hill.

145
00:11:43,536 --> 00:11:46,903
Wait a minute. No more "Mrs. Hill."

146
00:11:47,473 --> 00:11:51,307
From now on,
you're going to be Helen Martin.

147
00:11:51,644 --> 00:11:55,239
- Helen Martin?
- I'm going to be Adelle Stuart.

148
00:11:56,048 --> 00:11:57,538
Adelle Stuart?

149
00:11:58,150 --> 00:12:00,118
New names and new lives.

150
00:12:01,253 --> 00:12:02,242
New lives.

151
00:12:02,321 --> 00:12:04,983
- A whole new shuffle for both of us, okay?
- Okay.

152
00:12:05,057 --> 00:12:09,426
And if the school catches on,
then we'll hire a high-priced lawyer.

153
00:12:09,495 --> 00:12:12,726
Maybe even Clarence Darrow,
for an appeal, for the boys.

154
00:12:12,798 --> 00:12:15,932
And anyway, we'll be 2,000 miles away
from everything, including that.

155
00:12:16,000 --> 00:12:17,451
[Telephone Ringing]

156
00:12:22,139 --> 00:12:23,452
Hello?

157
00:12:25,111 --> 00:12:27,272
<i>[Man]: Your light went on...</i>

158
00:12:27,346 --> 00:12:30,372
<i>... so I know you're awake.</i>

159
00:12:31,283 --> 00:12:34,548
You will kindly refrain
from disturbing us further!

160
00:12:39,625 --> 00:12:41,456
H-He's been watching us.

161
00:12:56,942 --> 00:12:58,739
[Helen]:
Come away from there.

162
00:12:59,378 --> 00:13:01,903
Come away from there, Adelle Stuart.

163
00:13:08,087 --> 00:13:10,078
California, here we come.

164
00:13:11,389 --> 00:13:14,024
 [Piano music playing
and tap shoes clacking]

165
00:13:19,296 --> 00:13:21,097
[Sound Of Cars Driving
And Honking]

166
00:13:57,470 --> 00:13:59,233
That's it, girls.

167
00:13:59,538 --> 00:14:02,200
Swing those arms out. Turn around, now.

168
00:14:03,109 --> 00:14:05,543
Good, swing the arms.
Go right around, that's it.

169
00:14:08,647 --> 00:14:10,911
And one more turn.

170
00:14:11,283 --> 00:14:12,580
That's perfect, yes.

171
00:14:14,286 --> 00:14:17,016
And around, and kick.

172
00:14:17,323 --> 00:14:19,018
And turn.

173
00:14:19,358 --> 00:14:21,189
And turn, turn.

174
00:14:22,094 --> 00:14:23,959
Lift those hands.
[Inaudible]

175
00:14:24,897 --> 00:14:26,626
Lift. Good.

176
00:14:30,669 --> 00:14:32,569
Very good, Winona. Good.

177
00:14:33,272 --> 00:14:35,797
Now, okay, twist, twist.

178
00:14:53,159 --> 00:14:57,255
Good. Time's up for today, kids.
You're going to be just swell.

179
00:14:56,744 --> 00:14:57,977
[Children All Laughing]

180
00:14:58,764 --> 00:15:03,667
Miss Stuart, have any of those talent
scouts said they're coming to the recital?

181
00:15:03,769 --> 00:15:07,728
We heard from Universal and Columbia,
but not from the other studios.

182
00:15:07,807 --> 00:15:09,399
Well, you gotta have MGM.

183
00:15:09,475 --> 00:15:13,605
[Woman]: Oh, Miss Stuart,
you know  how bad Charlene's eyes are,
the trouble she has with them.

184
00:15:13,679 --> 00:15:15,510
If you put her in the back row...

185
00:15:15,581 --> 00:15:17,742
I haven't forgotten, Mrs. Baker.

186
00:15:17,817 --> 00:15:20,217
- Mrs. Barker.
- I haven't forgotten.

187
00:15:27,359 --> 00:15:30,590
Mrs. Palmer, excuse me.
Winona, what's the matter?

188
00:15:30,663 --> 00:15:32,824
You were doing just great last time.

189
00:15:33,299 --> 00:15:35,460
I hate my costume.

190
00:15:35,868 --> 00:15:38,336
We do like all the girls to dress alike.

191
00:15:38,470 --> 00:15:40,267
It's her father's idea.

192
00:15:40,339 --> 00:15:43,638
He had it made up special,
in four different colors.

193
00:15:43,742 --> 00:15:45,767
Could you speak to him, being the mother?

194
00:15:45,845 --> 00:15:47,779
I'm only the housekeeper.

195
00:15:47,847 --> 00:15:50,645
We don't talk about my mother. She's bad.

196
00:15:52,718 --> 00:15:56,313
I'll try to explain it to Mr. Palmer,
but I doubt he'll listen.

197
00:15:56,455 --> 00:15:57,854
He's a Texas man.

198
00:15:57,923 --> 00:15:59,356
Come on, Winona.

199
00:15:59,425 --> 00:16:01,393
Look at the little lady.

200
00:16:04,563 --> 00:16:06,861
Don't stare, Donna. It's rude.

201
00:16:12,638 --> 00:16:14,838
Miss Stuart, now,
you won't forget, will you?

202
00:16:14,906 --> 00:16:16,105
No, I won't.

203
00:16:16,173 --> 00:16:17,908
[Sound Of Jackhammer]

204
00:16:30,354 --> 00:16:31,388
Helen?

205
00:16:31,455 --> 00:16:32,806
[Door Closing]

206
00:16:36,343 --> 00:16:37,443
Helen?

207
00:16:58,465 --> 00:16:59,965
[Birds Singing]

208
00:17:00,034 --> 00:17:01,700
Helen?

209
00:17:01,720 --> 00:17:03,381
Poor little thing. Ah.

210
00:17:03,237 --> 00:17:04,430
Oh.

211
00:17:05,372 --> 00:17:06,672
Oh, Adelle.

212
00:17:07,459 --> 00:17:09,723
My little white one...

213
00:17:10,496 --> 00:17:12,896
...she doesn't feel well.

214
00:17:15,234 --> 00:17:17,429
The poor thing doesn't feel well.

215
00:17:21,407 --> 00:17:22,533
Here we are.

216
00:17:23,742 --> 00:17:27,143
The poor little thing.
You know, she's expecting.

217
00:17:27,212 --> 00:17:30,511
- You know what they say about rabbits.
- No, what?

218
00:17:30,849 --> 00:17:33,579
What are you going to do with all of them?

219
00:17:33,919 --> 00:17:36,479
I'm going to love them, take care of them.

220
00:17:36,555 --> 00:17:38,750
Still the country girl at heart.

221
00:17:38,824 --> 00:17:42,385
But, all the same,
you're the Marion Davies type.

222
00:17:42,861 --> 00:17:44,226
Marion who?

223
00:17:45,064 --> 00:17:48,693
<i>Didn't you see Marion
in Polly of the Circus?</i>

224
00:17:48,834 --> 00:17:53,168
<i>No, I'm afraid the only movie I've seen
in five years is Sign of the Cross.</i>

225
00:17:55,674 --> 00:17:59,201
- Marion Davies is lovely.
- She's beautiful.

226
00:17:59,645 --> 00:18:02,239
But Adelle, I'm not one bit like her.

227
00:18:04,083 --> 00:18:05,345
You could be.

228
00:18:07,953 --> 00:18:10,217
Helen, you know how much
I read about show business.

229
00:18:10,289 --> 00:18:11,415
Mm-Hmm.
Yes, I know.

230
00:18:11,490 --> 00:18:14,926
- And how interested I am in everything.
- Yes.

231
00:18:15,194 --> 00:18:19,062
You know, it's to know what type you are.

232
00:18:19,765 --> 00:18:22,563
The public always looks for types.

233
00:18:22,634 --> 00:18:23,726
Yes, I know.

234
00:18:23,802 --> 00:18:26,828
Like, I am Jean Harlow, definitely.

235
00:18:26,939 --> 00:18:29,169
I think I've heard of her.

236
00:18:29,308 --> 00:18:31,572
She's English, isn't she?

237
00:18:32,711 --> 00:18:33,700
[Laughing] No.

238
00:18:33,812 --> 00:18:36,110
No, no, Helen,
she's from Kansas City...

239
00:18:36,215 --> 00:18:38,772
...and they call her "the blonde bombshell."

240
00:18:38,798 --> 00:18:40,093
[Laughing]

241
00:18:40,419 --> 00:18:41,477
Here, take a look.

242
00:18:41,553 --> 00:18:42,986
Oh, she's lovely.

243
00:18:43,555 --> 00:18:45,216
Oh, I see.

244
00:18:45,290 --> 00:18:47,656
Th-that's why you changed
the color of your hair.

245
00:18:48,260 --> 00:18:50,854
Oh, but you're
much prettier than she is.

246
00:18:51,263 --> 00:18:52,855
We could be sisters.

247
00:18:53,198 --> 00:18:55,632
The public always looks for types.

248
00:18:57,169 --> 00:18:59,296
All right, now...

249
00:19:00,973 --> 00:19:02,270
...here we go.

250
00:19:02,908 --> 00:19:04,671
There we are.

251
00:19:05,377 --> 00:19:06,969
There we go.

252
00:19:08,781 --> 00:19:10,271
And there we are.

253
00:19:11,817 --> 00:19:12,749
There.

254
00:19:15,320 --> 00:19:17,948
- Something the matter?
- No.

255
00:19:19,925 --> 00:19:22,189
I know how it feels
to have your hair cut off.

256
00:19:22,261 --> 00:19:24,161
Here, look at yourself.

257
00:19:24,396 --> 00:19:27,957
I used to wear my hair
longer than Jeannette MacDonald's.

258
00:19:28,600 --> 00:19:32,559
Isn't that gonna look nifty?
I mean, after I get
it shaped in a bit, huh?

259
00:19:33,405 --> 00:19:36,704
Adelle, why don't you wear
your wedding ring anymore?

260
00:19:38,210 --> 00:19:40,508
A ring doesn't mean a marriage.

261
00:19:41,480 --> 00:19:43,778
Anyway, that's in the past now.

262
00:19:44,450 --> 00:19:46,748
Oh, I hate to
think about the past.

263
00:19:48,320 --> 00:19:50,345
Sometimes I can't help it.

264
00:19:51,924 --> 00:19:53,585
You mean, the boys?

265
00:19:54,726 --> 00:19:56,694
No, further back than that.

266
00:19:57,062 --> 00:20:00,361
Lenny's father. How he died.

267
00:20:01,834 --> 00:20:03,062
Tell me.

268
00:20:04,503 --> 00:20:07,028
You know we had a little farm.

269
00:20:07,306 --> 00:20:10,104
One morning, it was a lovely day...

270
00:20:10,409 --> 00:20:12,377
...I made him a picnic lunch...

271
00:20:12,444 --> 00:20:15,106
...and I took Lenny
and I went out into the field.

272
00:20:15,314 --> 00:20:17,475
We were going to have a ride
on the plough.

273
00:20:18,050 --> 00:20:19,608
<i>And we started out...</i>

274
00:20:20,586 --> 00:20:23,146
...and then the harness seemed
to come loose...

275
00:20:23,789 --> 00:20:25,723
...and Matt got off to fix it.

276
00:20:26,892 --> 00:20:29,292
And then something frightened the horses.

277
00:20:28,125 --> 00:20:29,309
[[Horses Neighing]

278
00:20:30,095 --> 00:20:32,063
And I couldn't hold them.

279
00:20:33,832 --> 00:20:35,993
And the blades of the plough...

280
00:20:37,736 --> 00:20:39,630
...they're big,
and they're much sharper than they look.

281
00:20:39,636 --> 00:20:41,083
[Scraping]

282
00:20:43,809 --> 00:20:44,867
He fell.

283
00:20:47,012 --> 00:20:48,240
Matt fell.

284
00:20:50,082 --> 00:20:51,071
He fell.

285
00:20:52,985 --> 00:20:55,044
And Lenny saw it.

286
00:20:57,923 --> 00:21:00,414
He saw it all, and he blamed me for...

287
00:21:01,460 --> 00:21:03,223
...ever afterwards...

288
00:21:03,428 --> 00:21:06,329
...for not being able to save his father.

289
00:21:10,102 --> 00:21:13,003
But you said he was only four years old.

290
00:21:13,572 --> 00:21:16,507
He was too young
to think anything like that.

291
00:21:17,976 --> 00:21:20,171
But children do, they do somehow.

292
00:21:21,013 --> 00:21:24,847
They look at you,
and they just make you feel guilty.

293
00:21:29,221 --> 00:21:32,850
You have to see yourself full-length
to get the whole effect.

294
00:21:32,925 --> 00:21:35,450
It's lovely, Adelle,
lovely.

295
00:21:35,508 --> 00:21:36,932
[Kissing]

296
00:21:37,462 --> 00:21:39,123
- Oh, Thank you.
- It's perfect.

297
00:21:45,671 --> 00:21:47,605
I startled you. I'm so sorry.

298
00:21:47,706 --> 00:21:51,164
But the front door was ajar,
so I just came straight up.

299
00:21:51,310 --> 00:21:53,005
You should have rung the bell.

300
00:21:53,078 --> 00:21:55,808
I hate to spoil an entrance, I'm afraid.

301
00:21:56,181 --> 00:21:58,274
Are you Miss Stuart?

302
00:21:58,517 --> 00:22:02,078
No. I am Helen Martin,
Miss Stuart's partner.

303
00:22:02,688 --> 00:22:06,317
But I've heard excellent reports of you
in the profession.

304
00:22:06,391 --> 00:22:09,827
I give private lessons, you see,
in voice and diction...

305
00:22:09,895 --> 00:22:12,523
...to a few moppets
with ambitious mothers.

306
00:22:12,831 --> 00:22:16,528
Among these is your Charlene Barker...

307
00:22:16,602 --> 00:22:18,832
...a small but horrendous creature...

308
00:22:18,904 --> 00:22:21,634
...of absolutely no talent whatsoever.
[Chuckling]

309
00:22:22,808 --> 00:22:26,266
[Man]: Now, since the arrival
of the talking picture...

310
00:22:26,345 --> 00:22:28,438
Uh, Just what are
you trying to say to us?

311
00:22:28,513 --> 00:22:30,572
It's perfectly simple, my dear lady.

312
00:22:30,649 --> 00:22:32,742
Just concentrate for a moment, will you?

313
00:22:33,585 --> 00:22:35,951
Since the talking picture is here to stay...

314
00:22:36,154 --> 00:22:38,622
...your moppets must learn
to speak distinctly...

315
00:22:38,690 --> 00:22:41,090
...as well as shake their fat little legs.

316
00:22:41,193 --> 00:22:44,253
Now, why not extend your curriculum...

317
00:22:44,329 --> 00:22:48,663
...to include courses
in drama and elocution...

318
00:22:48,900 --> 00:22:50,697
...given by myself?

319
00:22:51,336 --> 00:22:53,201
Maybe he's got something.

320
00:22:53,639 --> 00:22:56,540
I mean, Shirley doesn't just dance,
she's an actress, too.

321
00:22:56,608 --> 00:22:58,473
We do not know who he is.

322
00:22:58,877 --> 00:23:02,412
My name is Hamilton Starr,
two "R"s, but prophetic nonetheless.

323
00:23:02,479 --> 00:23:04,178
[Chuckling]

324
00:23:04,182 --> 00:23:08,016
Now, a-at what time
do you conclude your classes
in the morning?

325
00:23:08,787 --> 00:23:10,652
- 11:00.
- Good.

326
00:23:10,722 --> 00:23:12,713
And that is when I shall return...

327
00:23:12,824 --> 00:23:16,590
...with some rather impressive
letters of reference.

328
00:23:16,695 --> 00:23:19,858
Until then, ladies, good night.

329
00:23:22,334 --> 00:23:25,303
"Good night, sweet ladies."

330
00:23:25,404 --> 00:23:27,099
<i>That's Hamlet, of course.</i>

331
00:23:27,539 --> 00:23:29,063
[Starr]: Oh, don't bother.

332
00:23:29,207 --> 00:23:31,903
I like to find my own way out as well as in.

333
00:23:32,311 --> 00:23:33,801
By the way...

334
00:23:33,912 --> 00:23:36,642
...shall I close the front door?

335
00:23:37,049 --> 00:23:41,110
Rather unwise, you know, to leave it open.

336
00:23:41,111 --> 00:23:42,111
 [Piano Playing]

337
00:24:17,923 --> 00:24:19,788
Girls! Girls!

338
00:24:20,058 --> 00:24:24,324
Now, kids, you've got the steps okay,
but we need to jazz it up a bit.

339
00:24:24,328 --> 00:24:26,638
Let me show you what I mean.

340
00:24:26,640 --> 00:24:28,273
[Children Laughing]

341
00:24:30,984 --> 00:24:32,184
 [Jazz Music Playing]

342
00:25:28,741 --> 00:25:30,042
[All Applauding]

343
00:25:32,264 --> 00:25:33,526
Well, you see
what I mean?

344
00:25:33,598 --> 00:25:36,533
Now, it's after 11:00.
I'll see you all on Wednesday.

345
00:25:38,870 --> 00:25:42,931
<i>On Goody, Goody, after the break,
make a note to speed it up a little bit.</i>

346
00:25:43,008 --> 00:25:45,772
Miss Stuart,
any word from the other talent scouts?

347
00:25:45,844 --> 00:25:47,573
We have Paramount coming, too.

348
00:25:47,646 --> 00:25:49,876
You didn't look at my Rosalie once today.

349
00:25:49,948 --> 00:25:52,109
How do you know
if she's doing good or bad?

350
00:25:52,250 --> 00:25:55,981
I did look, Mrs. Greenbaum,
and she's doing exceptionally well.

351
00:25:56,054 --> 00:25:57,282
Mr. Palmer?

352
00:25:57,355 --> 00:25:59,721
I'll see you on Wednesday,
Mrs. Greenbaum.

353
00:25:59,791 --> 00:26:02,385
They're very interested in Rosalie at RKO.

354
00:26:02,461 --> 00:26:05,862
- That's wonderful, Mrs. Greenbaum.
- She could make you famous.

355
00:26:05,931 --> 00:26:07,899
Yes, well, I bet she will.

356
00:26:07,966 --> 00:26:10,332
Why not bring her a little earlier
on Wednesday?

357
00:26:10,469 --> 00:26:11,458
I will...

358
00:26:12,838 --> 00:26:14,635
...if she's not testing.

359
00:26:18,343 --> 00:26:21,278
Mr. Palmer,
about Winona's practice costumes...

360
00:26:21,346 --> 00:26:22,574
You don't like them?

361
00:26:22,647 --> 00:26:24,774
I think they're dumb.

362
00:26:24,850 --> 00:26:26,875
Daddy, can we go home now?

363
00:26:27,652 --> 00:26:30,587
We do have a rule here
that all the girls dress alike...

364
00:26:30,655 --> 00:26:34,318
...and it makes Winona self-conscious
to stand out from all the others.

365
00:26:34,392 --> 00:26:35,381
Really?

366
00:26:35,827 --> 00:26:37,192
It shouldn't.

367
00:26:37,362 --> 00:26:40,456
I mean, if you got it,
why be afraid to let it
stand out, Miss Stuart?

368
00:26:41,281 --> 00:26:43,449
Well, if you've got it,
you don't have to draw attention
to it.

369
00:26:43,516 --> 00:26:44,676
Mr. Palmer

370
00:26:44,684 --> 00:26:45,901
[Chuckles]

371
00:26:46,438 --> 00:26:47,803
I'm hungry.

372
00:26:47,804 --> 00:26:49,290
Ah.

373
00:26:49,674 --> 00:26:52,666
That's a..that's a
very interesting subject,
Miss Stuart.

374
00:26:52,744 --> 00:26:55,474
I'd like to chat some more about that.

375
00:26:56,381 --> 00:26:58,440
Maybe over dinner tonight?

376
00:26:59,184 --> 00:27:00,412
Tonight?

377
00:27:01,019 --> 00:27:03,510
You got a date?
We'll make it tomorrow night then.

378
00:27:03,788 --> 00:27:07,053
- No, tonight'd be just fine.
- 7:00?

379
00:27:09,127 --> 00:27:10,424
I'll pick you up.

380
00:27:10,829 --> 00:27:12,296
Come on, baby doll.

381
00:27:12,364 --> 00:27:14,830
[Winona]: I want a
giant chocolate malted.

382
00:27:14,898 --> 00:27:15,998
[Door Opening]

383
00:27:17,100 --> 00:27:18,200
[Door Closing]

384
00:27:19,836 --> 00:27:21,096
[Car Door Closing]

385
00:27:26,676 --> 00:27:27,910
[Car Driving Away]

386
00:27:30,113 --> 00:27:31,480
[Helen Screaming]

387
00:27:32,284 --> 00:27:33,478
Adelle!

388
00:27:36,154 --> 00:27:37,485
[Adelle]: Holy Moses!

389
00:27:37,556 --> 00:27:39,023
Ladies, ladies, please!

390
00:27:39,591 --> 00:27:41,650
I found him up here.
He--he startled me.

391
00:27:41,726 --> 00:27:45,685
Your class was running a bit late,
so I decided to inspect the facilities.

392
00:27:45,764 --> 00:27:49,461
I'm so sorry if I alarmed your partner.

393
00:27:49,634 --> 00:27:52,194
Surprise entrances are one thing,
Mr. Starr.

394
00:27:52,671 --> 00:27:54,298
Snooping is another.

395
00:27:55,040 --> 00:27:56,701
[Laughing]
How right you are.

396
00:27:57,142 --> 00:28:00,634
I admit I am subject
to the disease of curiosity.

397
00:28:01,513 --> 00:28:04,971
Now, where do we discuss
these sordid business details?

398
00:28:06,051 --> 00:28:08,781
Do you still have your instinct, Adelle?

399
00:28:10,155 --> 00:28:12,020
He makes me laugh.

400
00:28:12,757 --> 00:28:15,851
We have the bond of humor, Miss Stuart.
I'm so glad.

401
00:28:16,194 --> 00:28:19,095
Mrs. Martin may still think
that I'm Jack the Ripper...

402
00:28:19,164 --> 00:28:21,359
...but my references are A-1.

403
00:28:21,733 --> 00:28:25,567
You could make a start
by calling up Constance Bennett.

404
00:28:25,904 --> 00:28:28,964
Constance Bennett, did you hear that?

405
00:28:29,040 --> 00:28:30,974
We still don't know a thing about him.

406
00:28:31,042 --> 00:28:33,237
But I have letters from the immortals!

407
00:28:33,878 --> 00:28:35,743
Let me see.

408
00:28:35,814 --> 00:28:37,941
Belasco, of course.

409
00:28:38,216 --> 00:28:40,980
And then here's John Barrymore.

410
00:28:41,086 --> 00:28:45,580
I played the ghost, not the gravedigger,
to his Hamlet, you see.

411
00:28:45,824 --> 00:28:48,816
George Bernard Shaw,
good enough for anyone, I should imagine.

412
00:28:48,893 --> 00:28:51,987
Then there's Herbert Beerbohm Tree,
Mrs. Patrick Campbell...

413
00:28:52,063 --> 00:28:55,226
Kay Francis!
Did you hear all these names, Helen?

414
00:28:55,300 --> 00:28:57,928
Those people don't mean a thing to me.

415
00:28:58,403 --> 00:28:59,768
But of course...

416
00:29:00,305 --> 00:29:03,172
...anything concerning the school
is up to you.

417
00:29:07,012 --> 00:29:10,846
Now what is there about me
that makes Mrs. Martin so nervous?

418
00:29:11,016 --> 00:29:13,883
Helen just isn't used to theatrical types.

419
00:29:14,019 --> 00:29:15,953
What? In this town?

420
00:29:16,021 --> 00:29:20,583
Even for this town, you're
a pretty special kind of ham, Mr. Starr.

421
00:29:20,859 --> 00:29:22,053
<i>Madame.
[Speaks French]</i>

422
00:29:24,029 --> 00:29:26,691
[Laughing] - Shall we go to my office?
- I should love it.

423
00:29:26,765 --> 00:29:27,754
Thank you.

424
00:29:29,334 --> 00:29:32,997
<i>[Woman On Radio]
Everywhere I go,
folks come up to me and say:</i>

425
00:29:33,438 --> 00:29:36,999
<i>"Sister Alma,
where do you get the energy...</i>

426
00:29:37,075 --> 00:29:40,533
<i>"... to hold three services
each and every day?"</i>

427
00:29:41,546 --> 00:29:44,344
<i>"From the pure love of God," I tell them.</i>

428
00:29:45,383 --> 00:29:49,114
<i>What I say to you now,
brothers and sisters, is repent.</i>

429
00:29:49,187 --> 00:29:51,417
<i>Repent and be saved.</i>

430
00:29:52,090 --> 00:29:55,389
<i>"There is no peace, saith the Lord,
unto the wicked."</i>

431
00:29:56,361 --> 00:29:57,350
Right this...
[Switching Off Radio]

432
00:29:58,845 --> 00:30:00,245
  DA DA DA
DA DA DA!  

433
00:30:03,034 --> 00:30:04,763
How swank.

434
00:30:05,303 --> 00:30:09,433
Is that what you're having for supper,
carrots and lettuce?

435
00:30:09,507 --> 00:30:11,099
That's for my rabbits.

436
00:30:11,176 --> 00:30:14,441
- You look beautiful.
- Thank you. Here, help.

437
00:30:15,246 --> 00:30:17,806
I took on Mr. Starr.

438
00:30:18,016 --> 00:30:19,643
I guessed you would.

439
00:30:19,751 --> 00:30:22,879
Don't let the Dracula act fool you,
really, he's just a show off.

440
00:30:22,987 --> 00:30:26,659
- I think he'll be a real asset.
- For your sake, I hope so.

441
00:30:26,673 --> 00:30:28,116
[Laughing]
[Buzzer Sounds]

442
00:30:28,793 --> 00:30:30,385
There's my date.

443
00:30:30,595 --> 00:30:32,756
- Well, good night, Helen.
- Good night.

444
00:30:35,033 --> 00:30:37,263
You won't be home late, will you?

445
00:30:37,469 --> 00:30:40,563
No, I don't suppose so.

446
00:30:46,295 --> 00:30:48,274
[Switching On Radio]

447
00:30:49,447 --> 00:30:53,543
<i>[Woman On Radio]
Oh, how I love these evening visits
with my dear friends.</i>

448
00:30:54,352 --> 00:30:56,411
<i>A chance for us to get together...</i>

449
00:31:02,360 --> 00:31:06,091
- What do you want?
- A cup of coffee, a pie, a sandwich.

450
00:31:07,165 --> 00:31:10,157
I've had nothing to eat in a couple of days.

451
00:31:10,468 --> 00:31:12,800
Do you know what it is to go hungry?

452
00:31:12,804 --> 00:31:14,014
[Chuckles]

453
00:31:14,072 --> 00:31:18,236
I lost my job six months ago.
It's a hard life out there.

454
00:31:18,943 --> 00:31:21,036
Why did you ring this bell?

455
00:31:21,479 --> 00:31:24,937
- Why pick on me?
- You look like you could spare a dime.

456
00:31:26,718 --> 00:31:29,812
I came out without any money.
Look for yourself.

457
00:31:29,823 --> 00:31:31,093
[Car Arriving]

458
00:31:31,289 --> 00:31:32,586
Here's my date.

459
00:31:33,756 --> 00:31:35,324
[Car Door Closing]

460
00:31:36,127 --> 00:31:39,494
This man wants a handout.
Do you have any change?

461
00:31:41,533 --> 00:31:42,659
Well, fella...

462
00:31:42,901 --> 00:31:46,962
...have a little something on me,
but let's not be bothering the lady.

463
00:31:47,405 --> 00:31:50,203
Not many people care
about other people anymore.

464
00:31:50,275 --> 00:31:53,369
Should be more people like her,
she gives a damn.

465
00:31:55,079 --> 00:31:57,070
Did he scare you, honey?

466
00:31:57,682 --> 00:32:00,480
Poverty frightens me, I guess.

467
00:32:04,055 --> 00:32:05,818
Thank you.

468
00:32:09,761 --> 00:32:10,955
Open it.

469
00:32:20,905 --> 00:32:22,429
Gardenias!

470
00:32:22,774 --> 00:32:24,765
Joan Crawford's favorite!

471
00:32:25,675 --> 00:32:27,109
 [Slow Dance Music Playing]

472
00:33:04,449 --> 00:33:08,783
I've never been on a gambling ship before.
It's so ritzy!

473
00:33:08,920 --> 00:33:11,582
With the money that they take in,
it ought to be.

474
00:33:11,656 --> 00:33:13,248
Okay, tell me something.

475
00:33:13,558 --> 00:33:15,651
- What?
- Anything about you.

476
00:33:16,060 --> 00:33:17,823
You ever been married?

477
00:33:18,663 --> 00:33:19,687
No.

478
00:33:19,764 --> 00:33:21,959
Just love them and leave them?

479
00:33:22,533 --> 00:33:24,660
Well, I can't say as I blame you.

480
00:33:25,436 --> 00:33:28,633
<i>I've got nothing against marriage.
It's just that...</i>

481
00:33:29,007 --> 00:33:32,499
It's the oldest story in the world.
I never met the right man.

482
00:33:32,577 --> 00:33:36,308
I bet you have a great time
playing the field.

483
00:33:36,447 --> 00:33:37,812
I know I do.

484
00:33:41,686 --> 00:33:42,948
It's a tango.

485
00:33:47,725 --> 00:33:49,022
Do you do the tango?

486
00:33:49,093 --> 00:33:51,891
Sorry, I don't think
even you could teach me to dance.

487
00:33:53,331 --> 00:33:54,855
It's all right.

488
00:34:20,358 --> 00:34:22,417
Mind if I ask the lady to dance?

489
00:34:23,761 --> 00:34:27,026
I think that's up to the lady. You want to?

490
00:34:28,099 --> 00:34:31,830
Go on, get up there.
You know you're just aching to.

491
00:34:35,239 --> 00:34:36,604
Thank you.

492
00:34:36,975 --> 00:34:38,738
I'll leave this with you.

493
00:35:58,321 --> 00:36:00,355
[All Applauding And Cheering]

494
00:36:28,953 --> 00:36:30,510
When can I see you again?

